<div class="links">[<a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="toggle_abstract(this)">Abstract</a>] [<a href="papers/icml2015_alecton.pdf">Paper</a>] [<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1411.1134">Arxiv</a>] </div>
<div class="abstract">Stochastic gradient descent (SGD) on a low-rank factorization is commonly employed to speed up matrix problems including matrix completion, subspace tracking, and SDP relaxation. In this paper, we exhibit a step size scheme for SGD on a low-rank least-squares problem, and we prove that, under broad sampling conditions, our method converges globally from a random starting point within \(O(\epsilon^{-1} n \log n)\) steps with constant probability for constant-rank problems. Our modification of SGD relates it to stochastic power iteration. We also show experiments to illustrate the runtime and convergence of the algorithm.</div>

